review_blob: Currently my favorite beer. The predominate flavor is caramel malt. It is sweet but not overly so. Medium mouth feel, somewhat light for the strength of the beer, but this is a good thing.

I did not find this aromatic nor did I get the thick white head others have written about.  Poured cloudy yellow-orange with a thin white head that quickly dissapeared leaving no lacing.  Easy to drink. A bit of carbonation bite and a bitter after taste.
Okay, it is not my style beer.  It is thin and low alcohol.  Might be good on a hot day.
Poured opaque dark brown with no head, no lacing no carbonation.  Primary flavor was from the oak aging.  Perhaps the barrel aging is not my thing.  To me this tasted like bad burbon whiskey.

Little aroma, clear yellow no head.  Flavor is faint a cross between a wheat beer and Belgian Golden Ale.
A summer beer for sure.  You need to be hit ant thirsty and the beer needs to be cold.

Aroma mild citrus hops. Appearance hazy yellwo-amber little head but moderate lacing.  Flavor not as hoppy nor as bitter as I would expect from a double IPA. Palate full bodied without being oily.  Overall impression smoother than I would expect from a double IPA. Hides the alcohol well.
Malty aroma and flavor. I would classify this as a Scotch Ale.Smooth with a peek of alcohol. I drink Vodka from the bottle, the alcohol is welcome.

My highest points came from appearance; creamy white head on crystal clear golden brew with pilsner effervescence. Smooth easy to drink but lacking in substance and flavor. Very inexpensive, a good choice when the beer money runs out.
No head, no carbonation but lots of black sludge.  The recommendedtwo-ounce serving should be followed, you wont want more.
Clear yellow with little head and not much noticeable carbonation.  Corn and alcohol. Yes there are better high test beers, but if you want to get hammered this is a good choice.
Carbonation is its strong point, taste is its low point. Reminds me of Milwaukees Best Ice.  The colder you drink this the better.  I suspect more corn than malt.
Aroma is of malt.  A great classic double bock. All that I hoped for.  Sweet malt flavor. I give it high marks because I like doppelbocks and this is a good one.
Crystal clear deep red brown with generous tanhead whichfades quickly leaving good lacing. Primary flavor is roasted malt. Mildly sweet, no bitterness.

Opeque golden yellow with a short lived white head which leaves no lacing.  The flavor is sweet and yeasty with a prominent spicy flavor I have yet to identify.  Classicly Belgian. Hides the alcohol well.

Pours very dark with very little head that disappears almost instantly.  Deep roasted malt, slightly bitter with a hint of coffee. Alcohol is undetectable. Easy to drink, but thin in body. I do not expect bo buy it again.
First impression: this very black, deep roasted brew should be call a stout.  The body or palate is just a little on the thin side.

A very good brew but thin. If the palate had a higher score the overall would have a much higher score. Id be happy to drink this any time, but Ill spend my money on higher octane, or fuller palate. P.S. despite what TheCEO says; it is better than Sierra navada Pale Ale.
I like strong high alcohol beers and expected to like this one; however this reminded me of sour cider. Palate was okay, medium, not to thin, but the flavor did not quite cut it.
Very drinkable.  Just a little thin. Good balance between bitter and sweet, but palate is weak. 3.5 better than average but not excellent.

Wow! I loved this ale.  Strong citrus aroma. Nice head. A good barley wine disguised as  pale ale. Appearance, who cares. Aroma, okay but not essential. The two catagories that matter to me are taste and palate. This wins in both. Two thumbs up.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: This brew shows the infulence of Duval on Ommegang.  Ommegeddon is cloudy yellow with a thick white head. My initial impression is that it is a cross between Duval and Victory Brewings "Golden Monkey"  It is a good addition to Ommegangs line.
Third on my list of Imperial Stouts but it is real close.  Very dark with a moderate coffee brown head.
UPDATED: AUG 8, 2007
Very disappointed.  Dogfish Head 90 and 120 IPAs are excellent.  This tasted like sour cider. Thin sour cider.  Will not buy again.

This beer was the high point of my vacation in Illinois.  Very dark brown with good lasting head. Malt and carmel with smooth finish.  I do not know if it is available in Central New York, but you can be sure Ill look for it.
Piney critus aroma. Pours dark and clear, I did not get much head.  Hops the primary flavor.  Best beer Ive had from Saranac.  They are local.  Ill buy this again.  A hoppy barley wine.

A new favorite in the Barley Wine category.  Pours clear amber with small cream colored head which fades quickly leaving little to no lacing.  Excellent combination of sweet malt with hoppy bitterness; hides the alcohol very well.
six 12oz bottles.  Will not buy again.  Flavor is good, but overall inpression is wattered down IPA.  Good bitterness, easy to drink but unsubstantial.
beer_name: River Horse Hop Hazard Pale Ale

review_blob: This is hard to describe.  I bought it because of the Mothers of Invention "Freak Out" lable.  Very disappointed, will not buy again.  I read several reviews and cant agree with most of them.  I discribe it as a slightly cloudy golden yellow, little head and no lacing. I dont consider it an IPA, not hoppy nor bitter enought. I find it to have an odd dull citrus flavor.  The only advantage it has over an American lager is its higher alcohol percent.

Can a beer have too much head?  Thick long lasting creamy white head, can be avoided by slow careful pouring.  An interesting, highly rated beer that I found disappointing, although it does hide the alcohol very well. It was too yeasty wheaty for my taste.  Still far ahead of American lagers.

The best thing about this brew is the label.  Overall I found it somewhat non-diScript.  More malt than hops but thin. I had this in draft at the brew pub and in bottle.  I was disappointed in the brew pub, very limited selection. I visited Three Floyds on my way from Syracuse to Chicago. Their Alpha King is a good pale ale but of Robert the Bruce, I like the name and lable
beer_name: Three Floyds Robert The Bruce Scottish Ale

review_blob: I liked this better than La Fin Du Monde by Unibroue although very similar.  I might have been influenced by the 1% higher alochol content.  Cloudy yellow with a creamy white head. This is a Belgian Ale with a bit of a kick.  Sweet.
Give me another year and I will rate this beer higher.  My first impression was that this is a Belgian Ale.  Hazy gold with a white head.  Sweet wheat perhaps a hint of cloves.  A good strong brew.
UPDATED: MAY 17, 2009

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: This is an okay drinkablr beer.  I bought this in a variety pack of Magic Hat beer.  I prefer it to American Lagers but not by much. Perhaps four tenths of a precent.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Obviously I did not like this beer.  The aroma was reminiscent of lemongrass. A hazy gold color, a decent head, but I did not like the flavor which reminded me of green tea.  As far as I was concerned, its strongest point was the palate. If had good mouth feel dispite its flavor. All in all Id drink a lite american lager before Id drink this again.
The flavor is the strong point predominant roasted malt balanced by hopps.  It is too carbonated and very thin on the palate. It is a lite beer amoung porters. Not likely to buy again.
Disappointed. Golden beer settled from the bottom up.  More comparable in taste to an American lager than to an Ale. Ill only chose this if my other choice is a lite beer.

Perfect score, no I could not give it a perfect score.  I had to give it a perfect score for palate.  It is full bodied, not thin not surpy, excellent mouth feel. I give it a perfect score for taste, I like other imperial stouts with differing flavors but this is excellent.  Appearance? It has the appearance of an imperial stout. That leaves deduction for aroma or overall, while my sense of smell is not overly acute I deducted a point for overall, why? I did not wish to give it a perfect score.  I suggest you try it and decide.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Amber Ale with a quickly diminishing white head with no lacing. Good mouth feel. Complex enought to give you both the malt and the hops. This is good.  I would not hesitate to buy this again.
Very drinkable, not sweet not bitter, not much character either.  Bettern then the average American lager but nothing I would seek out to buy.
UPDATED: JUL 28, 2007
A very drinkable porter, clear very dark with little head.  Good dark roast flavor but just a little thin.
A brew to my liking, sweet yet dry. Carmel malt with hops finish. Excellent.
This is the best of the Samuel Smith line, very smooth with no alcohol bite. A good balance not sweet not bitter.
UPDATED: JUL 14, 2007
beer_name: Smuttynose Big Beer Series: Imperial Stout

review_blob: This is a full flavored sweet brew.  My personal favorite.  It was unavailable in the US for about a year.  I was pleasently surprised to find it again.
